==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scar
<hw>Scar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF. <ets>escare</ets>,
F. <ets>eschare</ets> an eschar, a dry slough (cf. It. & Sp.
<ets>escara</ets>), L. <ets>eschara</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/ hearth,
fireplace, scab, eschar. Cf. <er>Eschar</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
mark in the skin or flesh of an animal, made by a wound or ulcer, and
remaining after the wound or ulcer is healed; a cicatrix; a mark left by
a previous injury; a blemish; a disfigurement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This earth had the beauty of youth, . . . and not a wrinkle,
<qex>scar</qex>, or fracture on all its body.</q> <rj><qau>T.
Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A mark left upon a stem or branch
by the fall of a leaf, leaflet, or frond, or upon a seed by the
separation of its support.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scar
<hw>Scar</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scarred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scarring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To mark with a scar or
scars.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet I'll not shed her blood;⟦br⟧
Nor <qex>scar</qex> that whiter skin of hers than snow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His cheeks were deeply <qex>scarred</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scar
<hw>Scar</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To form a scar.</def>⟦br⟧
